[{"_id":"21d9ca15-3ede-3f13-875f-5c39d2f859f1","authorName":"brutus","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","authorUri":"http://www.b.ro/","authorUserId":"","authorFallbackAvatar":"","message":"Do you have an example of implementing TCP KeepAlive on a TCP Client?","postId":"2009_05_tcpip-resources-46ef2fa4-a815-3b0d-9303-d2a327b08701","replyTo":"","date":"2012-04-23T23:29:36Z","timestamp":1335223776},{"_id":"fa5fc102-a6b7-37fd-a308-3594a118d8b4","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"3db7b6e14d9da42751e4bab03bc4d034","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com/","authorUserId":"","authorFallbackAvatar":"","message":"I do not have a code example at this time, sorry!","postId":"2009_05_tcpip-resources-46ef2fa4-a815-3b0d-9303-d2a327b08701","replyTo":"","date":"2012-04-25T04:41:18Z","timestamp":1335328878},{"_id":"4e3ce121-073d-3931-9ea8-21f03e068c3f","authorName":"Mrusman","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","authorUri":"http://www.blogger.com/profile/13587866915872326241","authorUserId":"","authorFallbackAvatar":"","message":"TCP/IP Illustrated, Volume 1 (The Protocols), by Stevens. and  \r\nNetwork Programming for Microsoft Windows, by Jones and Ohlund.   \r\n\r\ncan i download the above mentioned books free in pdf form from internet?","postId":"2009_05_tcpip-resources-46ef2fa4-a815-3b0d-9303-d2a327b08701","replyTo":"","date":"2012-05-11T17:47:08Z","timestamp":1336758428},{"_id":"d904dc12-b5a7-31ef-9d4e-f9d6b05ff76c","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"3db7b6e14d9da42751e4bab03bc4d034","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com/","authorUserId":"","authorFallbackAvatar":"","message":"I don't know of any legal way to do that.","postId":"2009_05_tcpip-resources-46ef2fa4-a815-3b0d-9303-d2a327b08701","replyTo":"","date":"2012-05-11T19:17:09Z","timestamp":1336763829},{"_id":"b4860b6c-59a3-3f1d-a0ff-5d0760c02c9b","authorName":"Anonymous","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"","authorUri":"","authorUserId":"","authorFallbackAvatar":"","message":"I remember when I started socket programming, the official Microsoft API documentation was only available in a Word document, which was weird. Beej had an excellent guide that got me through it even if it was geared towards Linux:  \r\n[http://beej.us/guide/bgnet/output/html/singlepage/bgnet.html](http://beej.us/guide/bgnet/output/html/singlepage/bgnet.html)  ","postId":"2009_05_tcpip-resources-46ef2fa4-a815-3b0d-9303-d2a327b08701","replyTo":"","date":"2013-08-02T03:11:11Z","timestamp":1375413071},{"_id":"68909e30-0a7d-11eb-a23c-e7649c2eb75f","postId":"2009_05_tcpip-resources-46ef2fa4-a815-3b0d-9303-d2a327b08701","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2009/05/tcpip-resources.html","replyTo":"","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"1fa9c37abc9f759d9232ee329df6c491","authorName":"sean","authorUri":"","message":"Excellent blog..I have a question, Is it possible to keep a TCP socket session alive across a network disruption like, cable pulls, wifi signal drops etc...All the socket options, I have researched, I couldn't find a way to make a TCP socket survive a cable pull/disconnect. Appreciate any advise. Thanks.","date":"2020-10-09T22:18:50.978Z"},{"_id":"56e46660-0b6a-11eb-8bb1-21aed514f50b","postId":"2009_05_tcpip-resources-46ef2fa4-a815-3b0d-9303-d2a327b08701","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2009/05/tcpip-resources.html","replyTo":"68909e30-0a7d-11eb-a23c-e7649c2eb75f","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"TCP/IP keeps its connection by default, in spite of network disruption; there's nothing you need to do. As long as there is a new network path by the time the next packet is sent, the connection just continues working on the new path.\r\n\r\nI suspect what you may be observing is a special behavior Microsoft added to their OS: if a network cable is physically disconnected from the computer, Windows will immediately error-out any sockets using that connection. I don't think this \"feature\" can be disabled.","date":"2020-10-11T02:34:51.957Z"}]